{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01Mfc487K1QGfFdsHSAjnwhn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze this multi-tier caching layer and determine the minimum test level for each behavior.\n\nThe issue describes:\n- Cache key generation from query parameters\n- TTL computation based on data freshness rules\n- Eviction strategy selection (LRU/LFU) based on memory pressure\n- Cache invalidation on underlying data changes\n- Entry removal according to eviction policy\n\nLet me go through each behavior:\n\n## Behavior 1: Cache keys generated from identical parameters are identical; different parameters never collide\n\n**Analysis:**\n- This is pure deterministic logic — take query parameters, hash/generate a key\n- No I/O, no external dependencies, no real infrastructure needed\n- A unit test with direct calls to the key generation function should catch any failure\n- Mock testing? Mocking the key generator would just pass tautologically — not useful\n- Does it need a real database? No, the key is generated before any DB call\n- Does it need multiple modules? The key generator is a discrete function\n- Could a pure in-process mock miss this? No — the logic is deterministic\n- Real infrastructure? No network, no subprocess, no filesystem needed\n- LLM dependency? No\n- This is **Unit** level\n\n**Level probabilities:**\n- Unit: 0.95 (almost certain this is sufficient)\n- Integration: 0.04 (only if we need to test key collision across multiple caching layers, unlikely)\n- System: 0.01 (no real infra needed)\n- Agentic: 0.0\n- Workflow: 0.0\n\n---\n\n## Behavior 2: TTL computed correctly based on data category's freshness rule\n\n**Analysis:**\n- TTL computation is deterministic logic: given a data category, return configured TTL\n- No I/O, no external dependencies\n- Could be as simple as a lookup table or a function\n- Unit test: create instances with different categories, verify