{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01Mfc487K1QGfFdsHSAjnwhn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01UXa55SJseCPRhZQgxVMGvZ","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Cache keys generated from identical query parameters are always identical, and keys from different parameters never collide.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Cache key generation is pure deterministic logic with no I/O or external dependencies. Testing involves calling the key generator with various parameter sets and verifying identity (same input → same output) and non-collision (different inputs → different outputs). No mocking is needed—the logic itself is self-contained. A real failure in the key function (e.g., incorrect hashing, collision in the algorithm, parameter ordering ignored) is directly caught by Unit tests.","test_description":"Create parameterized tests covering identical parameter sets (verify output is identical across multiple calls), collision detection across varied parameter combinations (verify different inputs yield different keys), and edge cases (empty parameters, special characters, parameter order sensitivity). Use assertions on key equality and inequality.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.95,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The TTL for a cache entry is computed correctly based on the data category's configured freshness rule (e.g., user profiles = 5 minutes, product catalog = 1 hour).","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"TTL computation is deterministic logic: given a data category and a freshness configuration rule, compute and return the correct TTL value. No I/O, database access, or external dependencies are required. The test injects real (or test) configuration data and verifies the computed TTL against expected values. A real failure (wrong TTL calculation, misconfigured rules, incorrect lookup) is caught at Unit level.","test_description":"Test TTL computation for each configured data category with parameterized tests. Inject configuration rules (e.g., 'user-profiles' → 300 seconds, 'product-catalog' → 3600 seconds) and verify that each category returns its configured TTL. Include edge cases (missing categories, zero TTL, maximum TTL).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.92,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When memory usage exceeds the configured threshold, the eviction strategy switches from LRU to LFU as specified in the configuration.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"While the strategy-selection logic is deterministic (memory > threshold → select LFU), a pure in-process Unit test would miss the real failure: the cache system never monitors memory or never checks the strategy field after switching. A Unit test that directly calls the strategy selector with mocked memory values would pass even if the cache layer ignores the result. An Integration test must wire together memory monitoring, threshold detection, cache state, and verify that the cache's eviction behavior actually changes when memory pressure increases. This catches the failure of the system not responding to memory conditions.","test_description":"Set up an Integration test with a cache instance, memory monitoring component, and configured threshold. Populate the cache, trigger memory measurement below the threshold, verify strategy is LRU. Then simulate or trigger memory above the threshold, verify strategy switches to LFU and cache behavior changes (e.g., eviction method changes). Monitor state across multiple operations to ensure strategy persistence.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A write to the underlying PostgreSQL table invalidates all cache entries whose keys match the affected rows.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior involves the interaction between the database layer and the cache layer. A pure in-process Unit test with mocked database writes would miss the real failure: database write events are never detected or matched to cache keys. The real failure is in the integration—the cache layer not observing writes, the detection mechanism failing, or the invalidation logic not executing. An Integration test must include a real (or realistic) database client, a populated cache, and the application logic (trigger-based or application-side) that detects writes and invalidates matching entries. Testing with a mock DB that doesn't faithfully replicate write detection would hide the failure.","test_description":"Insert cache entries with known keys into a populated cache. Execute a database write (INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE) that affects rows corresponding to those cache keys. Verify that the cache entries are invalidated (removed or marked stale) immediately after or within the configured invalidation window. Use a real or well-mocked database client and a real cache instance wired together.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.82,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The eviction policy removes the correct entries—least-recently-used under LRU, least-frequently-used under LFU—when the cache is full.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The eviction algorithm is a discrete, deterministic function that takes a cache state (with tracked metadata: timestamps for LRU, access counts for LFU) and returns the key to evict. Testing involves setting up a cache with known access patterns, triggering eviction, and verifying the correct entry is removed. No I/O, database access, or external dependencies are required. Real failures (wrong entry evicted, algorithm ignores tracking data, off-by-one errors